/*
- An important thing to remmeber here is that we can generate the 2 GiBs of the
  dataset upfront and store it straight in DRAM. Or, which is slower, generate
  each dataset item on the fly when we need it.
*/

/*
- (1) What we want to achieve with the dataset is simple. The goal is memory
      hardness, which is a property of functions that are hard to evaluate
      efficiently without a large amount of memory.

      This is pretty fitting for RandomX, as CPUs have access to memory controllers, so that means reading, writing and prefetching up to tens
      of gigabytes of DRAM.

      Let's consider two ASIC designs to beat the CPU's slow external DRAM.

- (4) An ASIC for fast mode mining at the time of RandomX's introduction
      would simply be not possible, as 2 GiBs of memory would be economically
      infeasible to store on-chip. You would lose out of the advantage of on
      chip memory, and would have to use external DRAM, then at that point
      there is no advantage to a CPU.
*/
#slide(title: [(2.RX) Memory-Hardness])[

  #uncoverb(2)[*Goal.* Sufficient memory-hardness.]
  #uncoverb(3)[
    #l-m-meta[(Let's consider two ASIC designs!)]
  ]

  #l-m-hr()

  #uncoverb(4)[
    - *(1)* 2 GiBs of on-chip low latency SRAM
      
      #uncoverb(6, l-m-meta[(An ASIC for fast mode mining is infeasible.)])
  ]
  #uncoverb(5)[
    #v(1em)
    $==>$ Try to make light mode mining viable?
    #v(1em)
  ]
]

/*
- (2) ... So, this ASIC will opt to only store the cache, and execute the
      8 superscalarhash instances. Is that much slower?

- (3) Because the superscalarhash generator, which is a CPU simulator, tries
      its hardest to maximise the dependency chain for all the registers
      across the instructions so an ASIC can't just evaluate the entire
      hash in parallel. Since each instruction depends on the previous one
      maximally, OoO execution and the superscalar nature of CPUs will be
      able to evaluate it efficiently. An ASIC would lose a lot of efficiency
      on the performance front.

- (4) Also, it uses an incredible amount of power. Equivalent to just using
      external DRAM like a regular CPU.
*/
#slide(title: [(2.RX) Memory-Hardness])[
  Let's try a competitive light mode mining ASIC?
  
  #uncoverb(2)[
    - *(2)* Light mode mining, 256 MiB of on-chip memory, 1-cycle latency for ops.
  ]

  #uncoverb(3)[
    #set text(size: 0.8em, l-m-meta-colour)

    #v(1em)

    The average SuperscalarHash function contains a total of 450 instructions, out of which 155 are 64-bit multiplications. On average, the longest dependency chain is 95 instructions long.
  
    \[...\]

    #uncoverb(4)[
      It will have to execute 155 \* 8 = 1240 64-bit multiplications per item, which will consume energy comparable to loading 64 bytes from DRAM.
    ]
  ]
  #v(1em)

  #uncoverb(2)[*Result.*] #uncoverb(5)[
    No advantage over CPU.
  ]
]

/*
- (1) So, given that we know that the Dataset takes advantage of the fact
      that CPUs are superscalar, and that Dataset initialisation is uniquely
      memory hard in the sense that creation of an ASIC that calculates the
      dataset ahead of time compared to calculating the items on demand, either
      has no advantage over a CPU.

- (2) Could we stop here? Consider an alteration of the dataset side of RandomX,
      with a new hash function that takes in a fixed key K and a large integer N,
      somehow hypothetically being an index into some dataset item.

      Assuming this is a good hash function: have we done enough?

- (3) The answer is not really, we do win memory hardness, but the fact that
      the superscalar hashes are superscalar isn't that useful. It's only to
      discourage the light mining ASIC design by burning huge amounts of energy,
      giving it no advantage over superscalar CPU designs.

      We only win memory hardness here.

      So, we need a whole other execution model, the RandomX VM, where as much
      of the CPU's capabilities are used.

- (9) Remember the goal here, we want to make the creation of an ASIC for RandomX
      as economically infeasible as possible, and which if an ASIC were to be
      created, it would resemble a CPU.

      Hence, every feature we include here that CPUs are optimised for, will
      increase the die area, the chip size, which will make it very expensive.
*/
#slide-background(
  background: image("randomx architecture dataset 1.png", fit: "cover", width: 110%, height: 110%),
  inset: 1em,
)[
  #set align(top)
  #set text(size: 0.9em)

  #grid(columns: (12fr, 10fr), gutter: 0em, gc[], gc[
    #uncoverb(2)[*Could we stop here?*]

    #uncoverb(3)[
      Not really.
    
      #l-m-meta[(Superscalar enables memory-hardness.)]
    ]

    #l-m-hr()

    #uncoverb(4)[- Superscalar instructions.]

    #uncoverb(5)[
      - Readable/writable memory.
      
        #l-m-meta[(L1, L2, L3 caches.)]
    ]

    #uncoverb(6)[
      - Instruction decoding.
      
        #l-m-meta[(μop cache)]
    ]
    
    #uncoverb(7)[
      - Floating point (IEE754), and ALU.
    ]

    #uncoverb(8)[
      - Branches/branch prediction.
    ]

    #uncoverb(9)[
      #l-m-hr()

      *Each increases die area for an ASIC!*
    ]
  ])
]

